{"title_page": "Jon Akass", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n'''John Ewart Akass''' (16 July 1933 &ndash; 4 June 1990), known as '''Jon Akass''', was a British [[Fleet Street]] journalist.<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' by [[Keith Waterhouse]], ''Write after lunch'', Tuesday June 5, 1990</ref><ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1990/06/07/page/115/article/veteran-fleet-street-columnist-jon-akass-56|title=Veteran Fleet Street columnist Jon Akass|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=7 June 1990|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref>  His obituary by [[Keith Waterhouse]] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' described him as a 'shambling Ustinov-shaped figure in a crumpled white suit, the ''[[Daily Express]]'' columnist Jon Akass forever looked either as if he was on his way to a good nap after a good lunch or as if he had just risen from a good nap in time for the cocktail hour and a good supper'.<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' by [[Keith Waterhouse]], ''Write after lunch'', Tuesday June 5, 1990</ref>  Akass was named British columnist of the year in 1976.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', January 21, 1976, p.4</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAkass was born in [[Bedford]], [[England]] and educated at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref>England BMD Indexes</ref><ref>Eagle News, Number 62, January 1991, p40</ref>  At the age of 15 Akass joined the London office of the <!-- Name change occurred in 1992. -->''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|Glasgow Herald]]'' as a teaboy. He worked as a reporter on a local newspaper in Lincolnshire before joining the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' in Manchester where he was responsible for the coverage of the [[Munich air disaster]] which claimed eight players of the [[Manchester United]] football team in 1958.<ref name=\"Griffiths\">Dennis Griffiths (ed) ''The Encyclopedia of the British Press, 1422\u20131992'', London and Basingstoke: Macmillan, 1992, p.71</ref> He soon moved to the London offices of the ''Daily Herald'' where he worked alongside [[Dennis Potter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wNWZ1ZqWWr4C&pg=PT36&lpg=PT36&dq=dennis+potter+jon+akass&source=bl&ots=GY1zvhLh0I&sig=YFPwKnYmBHiDrYtqR6dcAnrLi6w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TZUVVYiYPMzcaseRgdAH&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=dennis%20potter%20jon%20akass&f=false|title=The Life and Work of Dennis Potter|work=google.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkass stayed with ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', as the ''Daily Herald'' became, and continued with the paper when it was acquired by [[Rupert Murdoch]] in 1969 and underwent its transformation into a tabloid. A columnist, he joined the staff of Sir [[James Goldsmith]]'s ''[[NOW! (1979\u201381 magazine)|NOW!]]'' in 1981, two days before Goldsmith closed the magazine. He returned to his previous post, but was a columnist of the ''[[Daily Express]]'' in his last years. He was a personal friend of [[Michael Parkinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0ccrWk87YbkC&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=michael+parkinson+jon+akass&source=bl&ots=gW_TDA1bGT&sig=dDP-dTacjjSPrq7xDc07qkLP9uQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0pUVVbg80uhokuqB6Ag&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=michael%20parkinson%20jon%20akass&f=false|title=Parky|work=google.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkass died in [[London]] on 4 June 1990 and was survived by his wife, Peggy, and four children.<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akass, John}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Bedford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n'''John Ewart Akass''' (16 July 1933 &ndash; 4 June 1990), known as '''Jon Akass''', was a British [[Fleet Street]] journalist.<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' by [[Keith Waterhouse]], ''Write after lunch'', Tuesday June 5, 1990</ref><ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1990/06/07/page/115/article/veteran-fleet-street-columnist-jon-akass-56|title=Veteran Fleet Street columnist Jon Akass|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=7 June 1990|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref>  His obituary by [[Keith Waterhouse]] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' described him as a 'shambling Ustinov-shaped figure in a crumpled white suit, the ''[[Daily Express]]'' columnist Jon Akass forever looked either as if he was on his way to a good nap after a good lunch of as if he just risen from a good nap in time for the cocktail hour and a good supper'.<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'' by [[Keith Waterhouse]], ''Write after lunch'', Tuesday June 5, 1990</ref>  Akass was named British columnist of the year in 1976.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', January 21, 1976, p.4</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAkass was born in [[Bedford]], [[England]] and educated at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref>England BMD Indexes</ref><ref>Eagle News, Number 62, January 1991, p40</ref>  At the age of 15 Akass joined the London office of the <!-- Name change occurred in 1992. -->''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|Glasgow Herald]]'' as a teaboy. He worked as a reporter on a local newspaper in Lincolnshire before joining the ''[[Daily Herald (UK newspaper)|Daily Herald]]'' in Manchester where he was responsible for the coverage of the [[Munich air disaster]] which claimed eight players of the [[Manchester United]] football team in 1958.<ref name=\"Griffiths\">Dennis Griffiths (ed) ''The Encyclopedia of the British Press, 1422\u20131992'', London and Basingstoke: Macmillan, 1992, p.71</ref> He soon moved to the London offices of the ''Daily Herald'' where he worked alongside [[Dennis Potter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wNWZ1ZqWWr4C&pg=PT36&lpg=PT36&dq=dennis+potter+jon+akass&source=bl&ots=GY1zvhLh0I&sig=YFPwKnYmBHiDrYtqR6dcAnrLi6w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TZUVVYiYPMzcaseRgdAH&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=dennis%20potter%20jon%20akass&f=false|title=The Life and Work of Dennis Potter|work=google.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkass stayed with ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', as the ''Daily Herald'' became, and continued with the paper when it was acquired by [[Rupert Murdoch]] in 1969 and underwent its transformation into a tabloid. A columnist, he joined the staff of Sir [[James Goldsmith]]'s ''[[NOW! (1979\u201381 magazine)|NOW!]]'' in 1981, two days before Goldsmith closed the magazine. He returned to his previous post, but was a columnist of the ''[[Daily Express]]'' in his last years. He was a personal friend of [[Michael Parkinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0ccrWk87YbkC&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=michael+parkinson+jon+akass&source=bl&ots=gW_TDA1bGT&sig=dDP-dTacjjSPrq7xDc07qkLP9uQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0pUVVbg80uhokuqB6Ag&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=michael%20parkinson%20jon%20akass&f=false|title=Parky|work=google.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkass died in [[London]] on 4 June 1990 and was survived by his wife, Peggy, and four children.<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akass, John}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Bedford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AlexdeGrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Akass"}
